    88 24 t.controller.abort(); 116

    91 24 resolve(result); 119

    468 /** 570
    469 * Builds the token request options. Does not make the request, just
    470 * creates it's configuration and returns it in a Promise.
    471 */ 573
    472 function buildTokenRequest(env, code, state) { 574
    473 9 const { redirectUri, clientSecret, tokenUri, clientId } = state; 576
    474 9 if (!redirectUri) { 578
    475 1 throw new Error("Missing state.redirectUri"); 579
    476 } 580
    477 8 if (!tokenUri) { 582
    478 1 throw new Error("Missing state.tokenUri"); 583
    479 } 584
    480 7 if (!clientId) { 586
    481 1 throw new Error("Missing state.clientId"); 587
    482 } 588
    483 6 const requestOptions = { 590
    484 method: "POST", 591
    485 headers: { "content-type": "application/x-www-form-urlencoded" }, 592
    486 body: `code=${code}&grant_type=authorization_code&redirect_uri=${encodeURIComponent(redirectUri)}` 594
    487 }; 595
    488 // For public apps, authentication is not possible (and thus not required), 597
    489 // since a client with no secret cannot prove its identity when it issues a 598
    490 // call. (The end-to-end system can still be secure because the client comes 599
    491 // from a known, https protected endpoint specified and enforced by the 600
    492 // redirect uri.) For confidential apps, an Authorization header using HTTP 601
    493 // Basic authentication is required, where the username is the apps 602
    494 // client_id and the password is the apps client_secret (see example). 603
    495
    if (
    clientSecret
    ) {
    		 604
    496 requestOptions.headers.Authorization = "Basic " + env.btoa(clientId + ":" + clientSecret); 607
    497 debug("Using state.clientSecret to construct the authorization header: %s", requestOptions.headers.Authorization); 608
    498 } 609
    499 else { 609
    500 6 debug("No clientSecret found in state. Adding the clientId to the POST body"); 610
    501 6 requestOptions.body += `&client_id=${encodeURIComponent(clientId)}`; 611
    502 } 612
    503 6 return requestOptions; 614
    504 } 615
    505 1 exports.buildTokenRequest = buildTokenRequest; 615

    522 /** 634
    523 * This function can be used when you want to handle everything in one page
    524 * (no launch endpoint needed). You can think of it as if it does:
    525 * ```js
    526 * authorize(options).then(ready)
    527 * ```
    528 *
    529 * **Be careful with init()!** There are some details you need to be aware of:
    530 *
    531 * 1. It will only work if your launch_uri is the same as your redirect_uri.
    532 * While this should be valid, we cant promise that every EHR will allow you
    533 * to register client with such settings.
    534 * 2. Internally, `init()` will be called twice. First it will redirect to the
    535 * EHR, then the EHR will redirect back to the page where init() will be
    536 * called again to complete the authorization. This is generally fine,
    537 * because the returned promise will only be resolved once, after the second
    538 * execution, but please also consider the following:
    539 * - You should wrap all your apps code in a function that is only executed
    540 * after `init()` resolves!
    541 * - Since the page will be loaded twice, you must be careful if your code
    542 * has global side effects that can persist between page reloads
    543 * (for example writing to localStorage).
    544 * 3. For standalone launch, only use init in combination with offline_access
    545 * scope. Once the access_token expires, if you dont have a refresh_token
    546 * there is no way to re-authorize properly. We detect that and delete the
    547 * expired access token, but it still means that the user will have to
    548 * refresh the page twice to re-authorize.
    549 * @param env The adapter
    550 * @param options The authorize options
    551 */ 663
    552 async function init(env, options) { 664
    553 6 const url = env.getUrl(); 666
    554 6 const code = url.searchParams.get("code"); 667
    555 6 const state = url.searchParams.get("state"); 668
    556 // if `code` and `state` params are present we need to complete the auth flow 670
    557 6 if (code && state) { 671
    558 2 return completeAuth(env); 672
    559 } 673
    560 // Check for existing client state. If state is found, it means a client 675
    561 // instance have already been created in this session and we should try to 676
    562 // "revive" it. 677
    563 4 const storage = env.getStorage(); 678
    564 4 const key = state || await storage.get(settings_1.SMART_KEY); 679
    565 4 const cached = await storage.get(key); 680
    566 4 if (cached) { 681
    567 2 return new Client_1.default(env, cached); 682
    568 } 683
    569 // Otherwise try to launch 685
    570 2 return authorize(env, options).then(() => { 686
    571 // `init` promises a Client but that cannot happen in this case. The 687
    572 // browser will be redirected (unload the page and be redirected back 688
    573 // to it later and the same init function will be called again). On 689
    574 // success, authorize will resolve with the redirect url but we don't 690
    575 // want to return that from this promise chain because it is not a 691
    576 // Client instance. At the same time, if authorize fails, we do want to 692
    577 // pass the error to those waiting for a client instance. 693
    578 return new Promise(() => { }); 694
    579 }); 695
    580 } 696
    581 1 exports.init = init; 696
